From 33dfc6f39e277a287e6beddc5c08f8fbb9769248 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: doodcom <doodcom@vortex.local>
Date: Mon, 13 Jul 2026 04:02:49 +0100
Subject: [PATCH] Add Linux NVIDIA RM API i2c backend for slow-speed GPU RGB
 controllers

The kernel's /dev/i2c-* adapters for NVIDIA GPUs run at a fixed
100 kHz, so the Zotac Spectra RGB MCU (0x4A, 10 kHz only) never
responds on Linux and the Zotac 4A controller was Windows-only.

This adds i2c_smbus_nvrm, a Linux bus implementation that issues
transactions through the NVIDIA Resource Manager
(NV402C_CTRL_CMD_I2C_TRANSACTION via /dev/nvidiactl) with the
per-transaction speed-mode flag - the same RM control NvAPI wraps
on Windows. i2c_set_max_speed() maps Hz to the RM speed flag, so
DetectZotac4AGPUControllers() works unmodified.

To avoid double detection of devices already reachable through
/dev/i2c-*, the bus refuses transfers until a detector requests a
reduced speed.

Tested on a ZOTAC RTX 4070 Ti SUPER Trinity Black (19DA:4710,
N702E-1002), driver 610.43.03 open kernel modules: detection,
all modes, and color control work; no duplicates, no root needed.

Co-Authored-By: Claude Fable 5 <noreply@anthropic.com>
